</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="130" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="129" pageNumber="130">
Holarctic and transgressing into the northeast Oriental region, introduced elsewhere. Afrotropical records: South Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Hurley, BP" journalOrPublisher="Agricultural and Forest Entomology" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="159 - 171" title="A comparison of control results for the alien invasive woodwasp, Sirexnoctilio, in the southern hemisphere." url="10.1111/j.1461-9563.2007.00340.x" volume="9" year="2007">Hurley et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="130" lastPageNumber="131" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="130" lastPageNumber="131" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">
Parasitoids of woodwasps: 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Siricidae" genus="Sirex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sirex" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<pageBreakToken pageId="130" pageNumber="131" start="start">Sirex</pageBreakToken>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Geoffroy, 1785" authorityName="Geoffroy" authorityYear="1785" class="Insecta" family="Siricidae" genus="Urocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Urocerus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Urocerus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="A.Costa, 1894" authorityName="A.Costa" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Siricidae" genus="Xeris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xeris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xeris</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName family="Siricidae" lsidName="" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" rank="family">Siricidae</taxonomicName>
) living in conifers. Males mate with females while they are laying eggs. The female inserts her ovipositor down the tunnel bored in pine trees by the host woodwasp larva, to lay an egg either into the egg of the host or into the young host larva. On hatching the ibaliid wasp larva emerges from the body of the host and feeds externally (
<bibRefCitation author="Hurley, BP" journalOrPublisher="Agricultural and Forest Entomology" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="159 - 171" title="A comparison of control results for the alien invasive woodwasp, Sirexnoctilio, in the southern hemisphere." url="10.1111/j.1461-9563.2007.00340.x" volume="9" year="2007">Hurley et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="130" pageNumber="131" type="species richness">
<paragraph pageId="130" pageNumber="131">Species richness.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="130" pageNumber="131">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ibaliidae" genus="Ibalia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ibalia leucospoides" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucospoides">Ibalia leucospoides</taxonomicName>
(Hochenwarth, 1785) (
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Ichneumon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ichneumon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ichneumon</taxonomicName>
) ssp. 
<taxonomicName genus="Cynipoidea" lsidName="Cynipoidea leucospoides" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" rank="subspecies" species="leucospoides" subspecies="leucospoides">leucospoides</taxonomicName>
Hochenwarth, 1785 (South Africa; extralimital distribution throughout the Holarctic region and introduced elsewhere)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
